('Inpatient Hospital Discharge Utilization Report','"<ReportManifest xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" Id="0" Name="Inpatient Hospital Discharge Utilization Report" RptId="2AAF7FBA-7102-4C66-8598-A70597E2F824" ShowInterpretationText="true" Category="Utilization" IsTrending="false" PreviewImage="IPHospitalDischargeUtilization.jpg" ConsumerPreviewImage="" RequiresCmsProviderId="false" RequiresCostToChargeRatio="true"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit><Audiences><Audience AudienceType="Professionals" /></Audiences><InterpretationText>&lt;p&gt;How do I interpret the table?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Medicare Provider Charge Data (Inpatient). These include hospital-specific charges for the more than 3,000 U.S. hospitals that receive Medicare Inpatient Prospective Payment System (IPPS) payments for the top 100 most frequently billed discharges.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hospitals determine what they will charge for items and services provided to patients and these charges are the amount the hospital bills for an item or service. The Total Payment amount includes the MS-DRG amount, bill total per diem, beneficiary primary payer claim payment amount, beneficiary Part A coinsurance amount, beneficiary deductible amount, beneficiary blood deducible amount and DRG outlier amount.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For these DRGs, average charges, average total payments, and average Medicare payments are calculated at the individual hospital level. Users will be able to make comparisons between the amount charged by individual hospitals within local markets, and nationwide, for services that might be furnished in connection with a particular inpatient stay.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The latest data file can be downloaded from the MONAHRQ website under the &amp;ldquo;Resources&amp;rdquo; section. It is available in CSV format at http://www.cms.gov/Research-Statistics-Data-and-Systems/Statistics-Trends-and-Reports/Medicare-Provider-Charge-Data/Inpatient.html&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The downloaded file can be uploaded directly into MONAHRQ without making any adjustments.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Information is provided for each selected hospital by Top 25 Diagnosis Related Groups (DRGs). Table includes the following.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Number of discharges (principal):&lt;/strong&gt; The number of hospital stays (or discharges) for the selected DRG is provided for a hospital.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mean charges in dollars:&lt;/strong&gt; Hospitals determine what they will charge for items and services provided to patients and these charges are the amount the hospital bills for an item or service. This does not include professional (MD) fees. Charges are not necessarily how much was paid.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mean costs in dollars:&lt;/strong&gt; The average cost is sometimes reported for each hospital. Costs are the actual value of services performed (while charges represent the amount the hospital asked to be paid for services). Total charges were converted to costs using cost-to-charge ratios based on hospital accounting reports from the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS). In general, costs are less than charges. AHRQ adjusts the cost-to-charge ratios to work with this type of hospital data.&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mean Total Payments in dollars:&lt;/strong&gt; The Total Payment amount includes the MS-DRG amount, bill total per diem, beneficiary primary payer claim payment amount, beneficiary Part A coinsurance amount, beneficiary deductible amount, beneficiary blood deducible amount and DRG outlier amount.&lt;/p&gt;
</InterpretationText><ReportAttributes>HospitalFilters DRGsDischargesFilters</ReportAttributes><IconSets /><Filters><Filter Type="Hospital"><Values><FilterValue Name="Hospital Name" /><FilterValue Name="Hospital Type" /><FilterValue Name="Region" /><FilterValue Name="County" /></Values></Filter><Filter Type="DRGsDischarges"><Values><FilterValue Name="Major Diagnosis Category" /><FilterValue Name="Diagnosis Related Group" /><FilterValue Name="Health Condition or Topic" /><FilterValue Name="Procedure" /></Values></Filter></Filters><Datasets><Dataset Name="Inpatient Discharge" /></Datasets><Columns><Column Id="0" Name="Number of discharges" IsMeasure="false"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit></Column><Column Id="0" Name="Mean charges in dollars" IsMeasure="false"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit></Column><Column Id="0" Name="Mean cost in dollars" IsMeasure="false"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit></Column><Column Id="0" Name="Median cost in dollars" IsMeasure="false"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit></Column><Column Id="0" Name="Mean length of stay in days" IsMeasure="false"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit></Column></Columns><Footer>&lt;p&gt; Weighted national estimates from HCUP Nationwide Inpatient Sample (NIS), 2009, Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ), based on data collected by individual States and provided to AHRQ by the States. Total number of weighted discharges in the U.S. based on HCUP NIS = 39,434,956. Statistics based on estimates with a relative standard error (standard error / weighted estimate) greater than 0.30 or with standard error = 0 are not reliable, and are designated with a †.&lt;br/&gt;All statistics are unadjusted.
	&lt;/p&gt;</Footer></ReportManifest>"'),
('Inpatient Hospital Discharge Utilization Trending Report','"<ReportManifest xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" Id="0" Name="Inpatient Hospital Discharge Utilization Trending Report" RptId="47426256-5F4F-4996-8F4A-3A344E39D90E" ShowInterpretationText="true" Category="Utilization" IsTrending="true" PreviewImage="IP_HospDischarge_Util_TrendsReport - MQ.60.jpg" ConsumerPreviewImage="" RequiresCmsProviderId="false" RequiresCostToChargeRatio="true"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit><Audiences><Audience AudienceType="Professionals" /></Audiences><InterpretationText> &lt;P&gt;How do I interpret the table?&lt;P&gt;
 &lt;p&gt;Information is provided for each selected hospital by condition or procedure grouping.  Select the titles in the top row to sort the results.  Tables may include the following.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Total US: &lt;/b&gt;National numbers are weighted estimates from the &lt;a href="http://www.hcup-us.ahrq.gov/" target="_blank"&gt;HCUP Nationwide Inpatient Sample&lt;/a&gt; (NIS), 2008, Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ).&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Total US region: &lt;/b&gt;Regional categories are defined by the Census Bureau: Midwest, Northeast, South, and West.  Numbers for each region are weighted estimates from the &lt;a href="http://www.hcup-us.ahrq.gov/" target="_blank"&gt;HCUP Nationwide Inpatient Sample&lt;/a&gt; (NIS), 2008, Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ). &lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Total of all hospitals in this Website: &lt;/b&gt;Numbers are presented for all hospitals included in this Website.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Hospitals: &lt;/b&gt;Previously chosen hospitals are listed.  You can select a hospital from the list for more detailed results.  Detailed results include characteristics of each hospital stay (age, gender, payer, and race).&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Hospital County: &lt;/b&gt;The county for each hospital is provided.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Number of discharges (all-listed): &lt;/b&gt;The number of hospital stays (or discharges) for the selected condition or procedure is provided for each hospital.  All listed diagnoses include the principal diagnosis (or reason for going to the hospital) as well as any other conditions that coexist during the hospital stay.  All listed procedures include all procedures done for the patient.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Number of discharges (principal): &lt;/b&gt;The number of hospital stays (or discharges) for the selected condition or procedure is provided for each hospital.  Principal diagnosis means this is the condition chiefly responsible for admission to the hospital for care.  The principal procedure is the procedure that was done to address the principal diagnosis.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Mean charges in dollars: &lt;/b&gt;The mean or average charge is sometimes reported for each hospital.  This is the amount the hospital asked to be paid for services. This does not include professional (MD) fees.  Charges are not necessarily how much was paid.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Mean costs in dollars: &lt;/b&gt;The mean or average cost is sometimes reported for each hospital.  Costs are the actual value of services performed (while charges represent the amount the hospital asked to be paid for services). Total charges were converted to costs using &lt;a href=" http://www.hcup-us.ahrq.gov/db/state/costtocharge.jsp" target="_blank"&gt;cost-to-charge&lt;/a&gt; ratios based on hospital accounting reports from the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS). In general, costs are less than charges.  AHRQ adjusts the &lt;a href=" http://www.hcup-us.ahrq.gov/db/state/costtocharge.jsp" target="_blank"&gt;cost-to-charge ratios&lt;/a&gt;  to work with this type of hospital data.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Mean length of stay in days: &lt;/b&gt;The average or mean length of stay (LOS) is reported for each hospital.  This is the average number of nights the patient remained in the hospital. When a patient is admitted and discharged on the same day, it has a length of stay of zero.  A longer length of stay does not necessarily mean better or more care is given to patients.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;If you select a specific hospital you will get following.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Age group: &lt;/b&gt;Patient age in years is based on the admission date to the hospital and date of birth.  The number of stays in each age is reported.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Gender: &lt;/b&gt;The number of males and females is reported for the selected hospital and condition or procedure.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Payer: &lt;/b&gt;Payer is the expected payer for the hospital stay. Payers are grouped into general categories: Medicaid, Medicare, private insurance, uninsured, other, and missing.  The number of stays for each payer category is reported for the selected hospital and condition or procedure.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Race: &lt;/b&gt;Race/ethnicity of the patient as listed in the medical record.  Racial and ethnic categories are collapsed into larger groups based on US Census Bureau designations.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;You may notice some special codes in the tables.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Dash (-): &lt;/b&gt;A dash is reported when there are not enough data for the given selection.  There are many reasons there may not be enough data to report.&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;b&gt;Small number suppression: &lt;/b&gt;Small raw numbers may be suppressed to protect patient confidentiality.  In this case, a &amp;quot;c&amp;quot; appears.&lt;/p&gt;	
</InterpretationText><ReportAttributes>HospitalFilters DRGsDischargesFilters</ReportAttributes><IconSets /><Filters><Filter Type="Hospital"><Values><FilterValue Name="Hospital Name" /><FilterValue Name="Hospital Type" /><FilterValue Name="Region" /><FilterValue Name="County" /></Values></Filter><Filter Type="DRGsDischarges"><Values><FilterValue Name="Major Diagnosis Category" /><FilterValue Name="Diagnosis Related Group" /><FilterValue Name="Health Condition or Topic" /><FilterValue Name="Procedure" /></Values></Filter></Filters><Datasets><Dataset Name="Inpatient Discharge" /></Datasets><Columns><Column Id="0" Name="Number of discharges" IsMeasure="false"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit></Column><Column Id="0" Name="Mean charges in dollars" IsMeasure="false"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit></Column><Column Id="0" Name="Mean cost in dollars" IsMeasure="false"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit></Column><Column Id="0" Name="Median cost in dollars" IsMeasure="false"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit></Column><Column Id="0" Name="Mean length of stay in days" IsMeasure="false"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit></Column></Columns></ReportManifest>"'),
('Inpatient Utilization Detail Report','"<ReportManifest xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" Id="0" Name="Inpatient Utilization Detail Report" RptId="2AAF7FBA-7102-4C66-8598-A70597E2F825" ShowInterpretationText="true" Category="Utilization" IsTrending="false" PreviewImage="IPUtilizationDetail.png" ConsumerPreviewImage="" RequiresCmsProviderId="false" RequiresCostToChargeRatio="true"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit><Audiences><Audience AudienceType="Professionals" /></Audiences><InterpretationText>&lt;p&gt;How do I interpret the table?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Medicare Provider Charge Data (Inpatient). These include hospital-specific charges for the more than 3,000 U.S. hospitals that receive Medicare Inpatient Prospective Payment System (IPPS) payments for the top 100 most frequently billed discharges.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hospitals determine what they will charge for items and services provided to patients and these charges are the amount the hospital bills for an item or service. The Total Payment amount includes the MS-DRG amount, bill total per diem, beneficiary primary payer claim payment amount, beneficiary Part A coinsurance amount, beneficiary deductible amount, beneficiary blood deducible amount and DRG outlier amount.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For these DRGs, average charges, average total payments, and average Medicare payments are calculated at the individual hospital level. Users will be able to make comparisons between the amount charged by individual hospitals within local markets, and nationwide, for services that might be furnished in connection with a particular inpatient stay.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The latest data file can be downloaded from the MONAHRQ website under the &amp;ldquo;Resources&amp;rdquo; section. It is available in CSV format at http://www.cms.gov/Research-Statistics-Data-and-Systems/Statistics-Trends-and-Reports/Medicare-Provider-Charge-Data/Inpatient.html&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The downloaded file can be uploaded directly into MONAHRQ without making any adjustments.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Information is provided for each selected hospital by Top 25 Diagnosis Related Groups (DRGs). Table includes the following.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Number of discharges (principal):&lt;/strong&gt; The number of hospital stays (or discharges) for the selected DRG is provided for a hospital.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mean charges in dollars:&lt;/strong&gt; Hospitals determine what they will charge for items and services provided to patients and these charges are the amount the hospital bills for an item or service. This does not include professional (MD) fees. Charges are not necessarily how much was paid.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mean costs in dollars:&lt;/strong&gt; The average cost is sometimes reported for each hospital. Costs are the actual value of services performed (while charges represent the amount the hospital asked to be paid for services). Total charges were converted to costs using cost-to-charge ratios based on hospital accounting reports from the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS). In general, costs are less than charges. AHRQ adjusts the cost-to-charge ratios to work with this type of hospital data.&lt;/p&gt; 
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mean Total Payments in dollars:&lt;/strong&gt; The Total Payment amount includes the MS-DRG amount, bill total per diem, beneficiary primary payer claim payment amount, beneficiary Part A coinsurance amount, beneficiary deductible amount, beneficiary blood deducible amount and DRG outlier amount.&lt;/p&gt;
</InterpretationText><ReportAttributes>HospitalFilters DRGsDischargesFilters</ReportAttributes><IconSets /><Filters><Filter Type="Hospital"><Values><FilterValue Name="Hospital Name" /><FilterValue Name="Hospital Type" /><FilterValue Name="Region" /><FilterValue Name="County" /></Values></Filter><Filter Type="DRGsDischarges"><Values><FilterValue Name="Major Diagnosis Category" /><FilterValue Name="Diagnosis Related Group" /><FilterValue Name="Health Condition or Topic" /><FilterValue Name="Procedure" /></Values></Filter></Filters><Datasets><Dataset Name="Inpatient Discharge" /></Datasets><Columns /><Footer>&lt;p&gt; Weighted national estimates from HCUP Nationwide Inpatient Sample (NIS), 2009, Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality (AHRQ), based on data collected by individual States and provided to AHRQ by the States. Total number of weighted discharges in the U.S. based on HCUP NIS = 39,434,956. Statistics based on estimates with a relative standard error (standard error / weighted estimate) greater than 0.30 or with standard error = 0 are not reliable, and are designated with a †.&lt;br/&gt;All statistics are unadjusted.
	&lt;/p&gt;</Footer></ReportManifest>"'),
('IP Utilization detailed Report (stratified report) – Trending Report','<ReportManifest xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" Id="0" Name="IP Utilization detailed Report (stratified report) – Trending Report" RptId="4E94E281-8E7E-4B02-8567-72B4FA239F9E" ShowInterpretationText="true" Category="Utilization" IsTrending="true" PreviewImage="IP_Util_DetailedReport_StratReport _TrendsReport - MQ.60.jpg" ConsumerPreviewImage="" RequiresCmsProviderId="false" RequiresCostToChargeRatio="true"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit><Audiences><Audience AudienceType="Professionals" /></Audiences><InterpretationText /><ReportAttributes>HospitalFilters DRGsDischargesFilters</ReportAttributes><IconSets /><Filters><Filter Type="Hospital"><Values><FilterValue Name="Hospital Name" /><FilterValue Name="Hospital Type" /><FilterValue Name="Region" /><FilterValue Name="County" /></Values></Filter><Filter Type="DRGsDischarges"><Values><FilterValue Name="Major Diagnosis Category" /><FilterValue Name="Diagnosis Related Group" /><FilterValue Name="Health Condition or Topic" /><FilterValue Name="Procedure" /></Values></Filter></Filters><Datasets><Dataset Name="Inpatient Discharge" /></Datasets><Columns /></ReportManifest>'),
('Nursing home comparison report (up to five nursing homes) with individual measure scores by domains','"<ReportManifest xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" Id="0" Name="Nursing home comparison report (up to five nursing homes) with individual measure scores by domains" RptId="F2F2B7FE-8653-488B-8ED8-FD4417CD0F9E" ShowInterpretationText="true" Category="Quality" IsTrending="false" PreviewImage="NursingHome_Compare_Indiv_Meas - MQ60.jpg" ConsumerPreviewImage="ConsumerNursingHomeComparisonByOverallRatings.png" RequiresCmsProviderId="false" RequiresCostToChargeRatio="false"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit><Audiences><Audience AudienceType="Professionals" /><Audience AudienceType="Consumers" /></Audiences><InterpretationText>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;How to interpret content&lt;/strong&gt;
    &lt;br&gt;Each rating in the report is shown as a simple image along with a word or two. The words will tell you how a particular nursing home compares to the average rating of the other homes in the area. Going from best to worst, the rating will show that a nursing home is:
    &lt;ul&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;span class="ng-scope ng-isolate-scope"&gt;&lt;span class="rating-nursing"&gt;
  &lt;img width="155" height="24" src="themes/base/assets/stars_5.png" class=""&gt;&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;span class="rating-nursing--title ng-binding"&gt;Much better than average&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="rating-nursing--subtitle ng-binding"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;span class="ng-scope ng-isolate-scope"&gt;&lt;span class="rating-nursing"&gt;
  &lt;img  height="24" src="themes/base/assets/stars_4.png" class=""&gt;&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;span class="rating-nursing--title ng-binding"&gt;Better than average&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="rating-nursing--subtitle ng-binding"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;span class="ng-scope ng-isolate-scope"&gt;&lt;span class="rating-nursing"&gt;
  &lt;img width="155" height="24" src="themes/base/assets/stars_3.png" class=""&gt;&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;span class="rating-nursing--title ng-binding"&gt;Average&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="rating-nursing--subtitle ng-binding"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;span class="ng-scope ng-isolate-scope"&gt;&lt;span class="rating-nursing"&gt;
  &lt;img  width="155" height="24" src="themes/base/assets/stars_2.png" class=""&gt;&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;span class="rating-nursing--title ng-binding"&gt;Below average&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="rating-nursing--subtitle ng-binding"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;span class="ng-scope ng-isolate-scope"&gt;&lt;span class="rating-nursing"&gt;
  &lt;img width="155" height="24" src="themes/base/assets/stars_1.png" class=""&gt;&lt;br&gt;
  &lt;span class="rating-nursing--title ng-binding"&gt;Much below average&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;span class="rating-nursing--subtitle ng-binding"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;/ul&gt;
    &lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The information on this website comes from two sources:&lt;/strong&gt;
    &lt;br&gt;1. Yearly health and safety inspections of each nursing home that are done by state agencies. Health and safety information, and staffing information, come from reports on these inspections.
    &lt;br&gt;2. Monthly information that each nursing home submits to the federal government about each resident. Quality information comes from this information source.
    &lt;br&gt;
    &lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;What’s here?&lt;/strong&gt;
    &lt;br&gt;There are three types of information in this Report:
    &lt;ul&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Quality Information&lt;/strong&gt;, such as whether residents are receiving appropriate care what is happening to their health and ability to function&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Health and Safety Information&lt;/strong&gt;, such as number of health and safety problems found when state agencies did an inspection&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Staffing Information&lt;/strong&gt;, such as the number of nursing home staff available to care for residents during their stay&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;/ul&gt;
    &lt;br&gt;This information helps you compare nursing homes to each other and see which are better. You can compare up to 5 nursing homes in terms of their Overall Score, their Inspection Score, their Quality Score and their Staffing Score.
    &lt;br&gt;
    &lt;br&gt;&lt;strong&gt;How can I use this information?&lt;/strong&gt;
    &lt;br&gt;You can use this information to:
    &lt;ul&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;help you choose a nursing home for yourself&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;provide useful information for your loved ones if they need nursing home care&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;encourage nursing homes to improve their quality&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;</InterpretationText><ReportAttributes>None</ReportAttributes><IconSets /><Filters /><Datasets><Dataset Name="Nursing Home Compare Data" /></Datasets><Columns /></ReportManifest>"'),
('Nursing home profile report with summary and individual measure score by domain','"<ReportManifest xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" Id="0" Name="Nursing home profile report with summary and individual measure score by domain" RptId="87E04110-46B0-4CAE-9592-022C3111FAC7" ShowInterpretationText="true" Category="Quality" IsTrending="false" PreviewImage="NursingHome_ProfileReport_Summary - MQ60.jpg" ConsumerPreviewImage="ConsumerNursingHomeProfile.png" RequiresCmsProviderId="false" RequiresCostToChargeRatio="false"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit><Audiences><Audience AudienceType="Professionals" /><Audience AudienceType="Consumers" /></Audiences><InterpretationText>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong style="line-height:1.6"&gt;Ownership Type:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style="line-height:1.6"&gt;&amp;nbsp; Nursing homes can be owned by private for-profit corporations, non-profit organizations, religious affiliated organizations or government agencies.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Number of Certified Beds:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp; Certified beds are beds in the nursing home that have been approved by the federal government.&amp;nbsp; Larger nursing homes have more beds.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Number of Residents in Certified Beds:&lt;/strong&gt; Certified beds are beds in the nursing home that have been approved by the federal government.&amp;nbsp; When a nursing home has fewer residents in beds than the number of certified beds, they should have room for new residents.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Provider Type:&lt;/strong&gt; Whether the nursing home participates in the federal Medicare program, the Medicaid program, or both.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Is the nursing home located in a hospital?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Is the nursing home located in a continuing care retirement community?&lt;/strong&gt; A continuing care retirement community is a place that offers different levels of care for older people, including independent living, assisted living, and skilled nursing.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Date first approved to provide Medicare and Medicaid services&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Special Focus Facility:&lt;/strong&gt; Special Focus Facilities (SFF) are nursing homes that have:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More health and safety problems&lt;/strong&gt; than other nursing homes (about twice the average number of deficiencies),&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;More serious problems&lt;/strong&gt; than most other nursing homes (including harm or injury experienced by residents), and&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A pattern of serious problems&lt;/strong&gt;that has continued &lt;strong&gt;over a long time&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The federal government requires that Special Focus nursing homes be inspected twice as often&amp;nbsp; as other nursing homes (about twice per year). These visits are used to see whether the nursing home has improved the identified problems or is in need of disciplinary action.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Does the nursing home have a resident and family council?&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;Resident and Family Councils are organized groups of nursing home residents, or their family members, who meet to share ideas and concerns that matter to patients. Under federal law, all nursing home residents and their families have the right to form a council and hold regular meetings. Nursing home must provide meeting space and must listen to the council&amp;rsquo;s concerns and recommendations, but staff or visitors can attend meetings only if invited. Nursing homes may have councils that represent residents, or families, or both&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Accreditation:&lt;/strong&gt;Nursing homes can choose to be &amp;ldquo;accredited&amp;rdquo; by one or more organization that determines if a given facility meets its standards.&amp;nbsp; Some very good nursing homes, however, do not choose to be accredited.&lt;/p&gt;
</InterpretationText><ReportAttributes>None</ReportAttributes><IconSets /><Filters><Filter Type="Display"><Values><FilterValue Name="Basic Descriptive Data" /><FilterValue Name="Map" /><FilterValue Name="Overall Score" /><FilterValue Name="Quality Measures" /><FilterValue Name="Health Inspection" /><FilterValue Name="Staffing" /></Values></Filter></Filters><Datasets><Dataset Name="Nursing Home Compare Data" /></Datasets><Columns /><Footer>&lt;p&gt; The information on this website should be interpreted cautiously as there are both strengths and weaknesses associated with the data. You may want to use information from many different sources to learn about a nursing home’s quality, such as the long term care ombudsman''s office in your state or the state agency that inspects nursing homes. Many experts strongly recommend visiting a nursing home in person before deciding to choose it for yourself or your loved one.
	&lt;/p&gt;</Footer></ReportManifest>"'),
('Find nursing home with overall and domain level summary ratings report','"<ReportManifest xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" Id="0" Name="Find nursing home with overall and domain level summary ratings report" RptId="BA52B7B2-F4C8-4831-B910-1D036B94AE75" ShowInterpretationText="true" Category="Quality" IsTrending="false" PreviewImage="NursingHome_ListingReport - MQ60.jpg" ConsumerPreviewImage="ConsumerNursingHomeComparisonByOverallRatings.png" RequiresCmsProviderId="false" RequiresCostToChargeRatio="false"><IsChanged>true</IsChanged><IsDeleted>false</IsDeleted><SkipAudit>false</SkipAudit><Audiences><Audience AudienceType="Professionals" /><Audience AudienceType="Consumers" /></Audiences><InterpretationText>&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;How to interpret content&lt;/strong&gt;
    &lt;br&gt;Each rating in the report is shown as a simple image along with a word or two. The words will tell you how a particular nursing home compares to the average rating of the other homes in the area. Going from best to worst, the rating will show that a nursing home is:
